Unconventional Central Bank Governor?
Prague – Recently, there has been one-sided criticism of central banks in advanced countries.
The main points of attack are as follows: since 2008, monetary policymakers have been too active, their powers have expanded too quickly, and this is harming the economy.
This argument – which is strange because it is popular among ideologically unaligned camps, such as liberals and neo-Marxists – is fundamentally wrong.
Critics fail to understand that modern central banks are responsible not only for combating inflation but also for maintaining long-term price stability.
Price levels are like human body temperature; they can fluctuate within a range that is neither too high nor too low without causing severe symptoms.
In fighting deflation caused by weak demand and curbing inflation fueled by excessive demand, the central bank must be equally “aggressive.”
While the battle is completely symmetrical, the public's assessment of it is strangely skewed, especially in countries where people are financially conservative.
This includes my home country, the Czech Republic. Czech savers save very little, and the loan-to-deposit ratio remains far below 100%.
Czechs are concerned about inflation, even though the Czech inflation rate last year reached a 13-year low, and the National Bank of the Czech Republic, which I have served as vice-governor since 2013, has been working to eliminate deflationary risks.
Other common complaints about central bank policies since 2008 in developed countries are that these policies have redistributionary effects.
Naturally, but so what?
Any monetary policy action will reallocate wealth.
Raising interest rates makes savers happy, while cutting rates benefits borrowers.
Importers like strong currencies; exporters like weak ones.
For there to be an effect, monetary policy must have different impacts on different groups at different times.
This is not a mistake; it is the essence of monetary policy.
Some critics also claim that central banks have failed to meet inflation targets, so their activism was not only unnecessary but also ineffective.
Sometimes they even put these contradictory criticisms in the same sentence as if they were accusing someone of firing blanks and causing casualties.
The reality is that during and after the global financial crisis, central banks around the world succeeded in maintaining price stability and monetary purchasing power – and it was a truly remarkable success.
Without their intervention, their economy would have faced a catastrophic deflation, a sharp drop in asset prices, and a total collapse of both the financial and real sectors.
Clearly, strong action was the right approach to address the crisis (the role of central banks in the outbreak of the financial crisis is a different issue).
In a system that uses fiat money without intrinsic value, for purchasing power to remain roughly constant over time, the money supply must vary accordingly.
Therefore, price stability, rather than the quantity of money, is the key issue.
The expansion of central bank balance sheets reflects how deep the problems faced by many economies were after 2008.
In this context, the central bank has taken necessary measures to maintain purchasing power and price stability.
To them, there is no "activism"; only the eternal mission of what needs to be achieved.
If you feel that this assertion carries a note of arrogance, let me provide some evidence.
The people vote with their wallets.
If their purchasing power was severely damaged after 2008, they would naturally seek to exchange their currency (for another currency, precious metals, or other savings methods).
This is rare in developed economies.
Naturally, central banks in many countries have not hit their inflation targets.
(Central banks typically define the ideal economic "temperature" as a year-on-year inflation rate around 2%.
) But that's certainly unpleasant, though it doesn't lead to disaster, especially considering that some price deflation stems from supply, not demand, shocks, such as plummeting oil prices.
This shock benefits consumers and poses no threat to price stability, at least for net oil importers.
Consider this scenario.
A company plans to increase its sales by 2%, but the manager achieves this by increasing it by 1% each of the past two years.
Would you consider this company a failure?
No, probably not.
After all, private companies often have deviations of 10% or more between planned and actual profits and revenues.
Most companies' operating environment variables are fewer than those of the central bank.
既然如此，你如何期望无论经济环境如何变化，央行总是能够精准地实现其通胀目标？
必须澄清，我没有说中央银行不应该努力工作以接近其目标。
它们绝对应该这样做。
此外，它们也绝对不应该让通胀预期变得不稳定。
However, when judging central banks, people need to maintain proper discretion.
They do need to stop saying things that are not true – for example, that the central bank's arsenal of policy tools may not only be running out but has already run out.
Money policymakers have sufficient weapons and unlimited ammunition at their disposal to use as they see fit.
These weapons come in different calibers, and their effectiveness varies over time.
Not all weapons are suitable for all economies in all circumstances.
But the central bank's ability to create and destroy money theoretically is unlimited.
The central bank governor should tell the ignorant critics "enough is enough."
Our critics fail to clearly and credibly explain why price stability is not a worthy goal, what key goals the central bank should pursue, or what radically different approach they should have taken since 2008.
There is a simple reason for this: The policy approach adopted by developed country central banks since the crisis has been the right one.
In fact, that approach pulled our economy back from the brink.
You're welcome.
